<HEADLINE>
<P>
PROPOSITION 111 PROS AND CONS AND ENDING TRAFFIC GRIDLOCK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Your May 14 editorial ("Making a Case for Car-Pool Lanes") chastises Orange 
County for not enacting a "transit tax" as in neighboring Riverside County. 
Orange County voters have twice rejected a sales tax increase, and may reject 
Prop. 111 due to specific projects it would fund. 
</P>
<P>
The last I heard, we live in a democracy and it is our prerogative to vote for 
or against a measure based on merit. 
</P>
<P>
Car-pool lanes have proved controversial, if not unpopular. Caltrans and the 
Orange County Transportation Commission steadfastly refuse to permit an A-B 
comparison study of mixed-use and car-pool lanes in such key areas as traffic 
efficiency, cost-effectiveness and safety. 
</P>
<P>
Give Orange County resident some credit. We see gridlocked freeways, 
comparatively empty car-pool lanes, and plenty of self-serving statistics. 
</P>
<P>
A no vote on Prop. 111 will send a message to the transportation mavens that 
"enough is enough." 
</P>
<P>
RICHARD DEIGHT 
</P>
<P>
Buena Park 
</P>
</TEXT>
