<HEADLINE>
<P>
STATE JUNIOR COLLEGE TRACK CHAMPIONSHIPS; 
</P>
<P>
GLENDALE'S BECK GATHERING MOMENTUM IN INTERMEDIATES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By KIRBY LEE, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A single hurdle remains for Marty Beck. 
</P>
<P>
The Glendale College sophomore will attempt to cap an undefeated season in the 
400-meter intermediate hurdles Saturday night in the state junior college 
championships at Santa Barbara City College. 
</P>
<P>
Beck, bound for UCLA, posted the fastest mark in the state at 50.97 seconds en 
route to winning the Southern California championships last Saturday at 
Cerritos College, and he lopped nearly a second off his previous best of 51.84 
set in the Western State Conference finals April 27. 
</P>
<P>
"I can't be in any better shape than I am now," said Beck, who placed ninth in 
last year's state meet in his first year competing in the hurdles. "I'm not 
going to place ninth this year. I'm looking to win, but I'm going to run my own 
race." 
</P>
<P>
Melanie Clarke of Valley is the favorite in the heptathlon. 
</P>
<P>
However, the freshman from El Camino Real High has been slowed by a sprained 
right ankle. 
</P>
<P>
Dave Swanson of Glendale is the leading qualifier in the high jump. Swanson 
cleared 7 feet 0 1/4 inches in the regional meet. 
</P>
<P>
Rod Carrillo of Moorpark and Ryan Rapoza of Ventura will compete in the javelin 
and decathlon. 
</P>
<P>
Other local qualifiers include Glendale's Rick Provenzano in the 800 meters 
(1:53.60) and Marji Gilles in the triple jump (37-3 1/4) and heptathlon (4,008 
points), and Ventura's Jaime Galindo in the 5,000 (14:46.21) and Simone Cain in 
the 200 (23.97) and 400 (55.00). 
</P>
<P>
Competition will begin at 10 this morning with the heptathlon. The women's 
5,000 and men's 10,000 meters will be the only finals held today. The other 
events will be contested Saturday, beginning at 3 p.m. 
</P>
</TEXT>
