<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
PERU; 
</P>
<P>
MAOIST REBELS SUSPEND FIGHTING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A Maoist rebel faction said it is suspending military action in Peru while it 
reviews its anti-government struggle, but it vowed to resume its armed 
insurgency. In leaflets found in the Andean city of Ayacucho on the 10th 
anniversary of the Sendero Luminoso (Shining Path) uprising, rebels who claim 
to represent a splinter faction said they will lay down their arms to "evaluate 
all our brilliant actions of the decade and then return with new impulses and 
ideas." Three bombs rocked Ayacucho, birthplace of the Maoist movement, and a 
10-year-old boy was injured, police said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
SENDERO LUMINOSO (ORGANIZATION); GUERRILLAS -- PERU; TERRORISM -- PERU; 
BOMBINGS -- PERU 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA051890-0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 220712 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
May 18, 1990, Friday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
