<DATE>
<P>
May 18, 1990, Friday, Orange County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Orange County Life; Part N; Page 2; Column 1 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
470 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
SALES AND USE TAX REVENUES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Clipboard researched by Kathie Bozanich and Janice L. Jones / Los Angeles 
Times; Graphics by Doris Shields / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Nearly $18 million was gained by county cities during April as as result of the 
state of California's latest disbursement of sales and use tax revenues. 
Another $900,000 was received by county government agencies, making the 
county's total take $18,791,945. That's a 25% decrease from the March outlay 
received locally. 
</P>
<P>
Anaheim and Santa Ana were the two largest beneficiaries, taking in $4.4 
million between them, for 24% of the total. Costa Mesa, though, received by far 
the highest per capita amount -- $17.59 for each resident. At the other end of 
the spectrum on both counts was Villa Park with its $2,245 total (32 cents per 
resident). 
</P>
<P>
The $18.8 million received here was more than the amounts sent to either 
Riverside, San Bernardino or San Diego counties, but only about a third of what 
Los Angeles County took in. Orange County had the highest per capita amount of 
any of the five counties, though. 
</P>
<P>
Each month, city and county governments and other governmental organizations 
receive payments from the state in anticipation of actual sales tax revenues. 
In the fourth month, they receive a cleanup payment -- the difference between 
actual revenues and the amounts previously received -- plus the first advance 
payment for the next quarter. The amounts listed here are for the second 
advance payment of the first quarter of 1990. 
</P>
<TABLE CWL="3.21IN:2.33IN:2.22IN:2.33IN" WDM="ABS" NCOLS="4">
